#Asset Analysis

1. Student Records
Student records contain personal and academic information. If unauthorized users gain access, sensitive information could be leaked or misused.
2. Examination Data
Examination papers, grades, and results must remain confidential and accurate. Unauthorized modifications could affect academic integrity.
3. College Website
The college website provides important information to students and staff. Cyberattacks can make the website unavailable or damage the institution's reputation.
4. Faculty Information
Faculty records contain personal and professional information. Attackers may target these records through phishing or social engineering attacks.
5. Network Infrastructure
Routers, switches, servers, and wireless networks are critical for college operations. Malware or ransomware can disrupt connectivity and services.
6. Learning Management System (LMS)
The LMS stores course materials, assignments, and grades. Unauthorized access could compromise academic information.
7. Library Database
The library database stores book records and user information. Data loss can affect library operations and student access.
8. Email System
College email accounts are frequently targeted by phishing attacks. Compromised email accounts can lead to data theft and unauthorized access.
